Description:The combination of a series of physical causal relations, forming a dynamical course. 
            This relations may be material, spatial, temporal, structural or mixed in nature.|AboutDefinition:CombinationOfPhysicalCausalRelations

AboutDefinitionInText:A-Of-B means A as a component of a whole B, or A is located in the environment B. Compared to the structural relationship A-IsPartOf-B, the meaning of A-Of-B is focused on a sense of quality of a thing rather than its structure.

AboutDefinitionInText:Relative-Independent-AND(-RIAnd-) is applied to the situation where two or more elements are assembled together and related to each other in the sense of the question discussed on, but keep their quality unchanged. Logically (A-RIAnd-B) is-a A or B and A is-a (A-OF-(-A-RIAnd-B)) and B is-a (B-OF-(A-RIAnd-B)). A or B is-part-of (A-CAnd-B)

AboutDefinitionInText:Absolutely-Independent-AND(-AIAnd-) is applied to the situation where two or more elements are mixed together, all the elements linked by the connector -AIAnd- are unrelated to each other in the sense of the question discussed on. Thus (A-AIAnd-B) means A and B as two unrelated individuals. Logically, (A-AIAnd-B) is neither A nor B, but A is-a (A-Of-(A-AIAnd-B)) and B is-a (B-Of-(A-AIAnd-B)).

AboutDefinitionInText: Combination-AND(-CAnd-) is applied to the situation where two or more elements are combined together and they related to one another so strongly that their qualities have been changed. Logically, (A-CAnd-B) is-not-a A or B, and A is-not-a (A-Of-(A-CAnd-B)) and B is-not-a (B-Of-(A-CAnd-B)), but A or B is-part-of (A-CAnd-B).
